      <h1 class='title'>Defamation</h1>
    </div>
    <div class='commons-written-statements-sitting' id='content'>
      
      <cite class='section'>HC Deb 27 October 2003 vol 412 c47WS</cite>
      <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_47ws' title='Col. 47WS &mdash; HC Deb 27 October 2003 vol 412 c47WS' name='column_47ws' href='#column_47ws' rel='bookmark'>47WS</a>
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S6CV0412P0-04740'>
        <a name='S6CV0412P0_20031027_CWS2_218'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/dr-bob-spink' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S6CV0412P0_20031027_CWS2_218' title='Link to this speech by Dr Bob Spink' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/dr-bob-spink" title="Dr Bob Spink">Bob Spink</a></cite>
          <p class="first-para" id="S6CV0412P0-04740">To ask the Parliamentary Secretary, Department for Constitutional Affairs what plans he has to reform the law on defamation to enable quicker and less costly resolution of claims. [133867]</p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S6CV0412P0-04741'>
        <a name='S6CV0412P0_20031027_CWS2_219'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-david-lammy' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S6CV0412P0_20031027_CWS2_219' title='Link to this speech by Mr David Lammy' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-david-lammy" title="Mr David Lammy">Mr. Lammy</a></cite>
          <p class="first-para" id="S6CV0412P0-04741">The Government have no plans for further reform of defamation procedure. The <a href="/acts/defamation-act-1996">Defamation Act 1996</a> introduced procedures to enable quicker and less costly resolution of claims. The 'summary procedure' allows straightforward cases to be dealt with without a jury; damages are limited to &#x00A3;10,000. The 'offer to make amends' strongly encourages a claimant to avoid a jury trial on the level of damages where the defendant admits an innocent mistake. Both these procedures were brought into effect on 28 February 2000.</p><p id="S6CV0412P0-04742">The number of defamation actions started has dropped from 452 in 1997 to 128 in 2002.</p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
